# Unified Modbus Development Rules (TCP + RTU)

> For implementation patterns, templates, FB structure, MAIN wiring, and protocol-specific details, use the `twincat3-modbus` skill.

## Architecture

Every Modbus device FB follows this architecture regardless of transport:

```
FB_[Device]
├── VAR_INPUT:  Transport config, bReadEnable, bWriteEnable, tReadInterval, stControl
├── VAR_OUTPUT: stData, bError, bBusy, Read diagnostics, Write diagnostics
├── VAR:        Transport FB instances, _nReadStep, _nWriteStep, data buffer, _nReadNextStep
├── VAR CONSTANT: REG_*, READ_DELAY, WRITE_DELAY
├── Interval Timer (self-resetting TON)
├── Read State Machine  (CASE _nReadStep OF ... END_CASE)
├── Write State Machine (CASE _nWriteStep OF ... END_CASE)
└── FB Calls (outside CASE, once per cycle, at the bottom)
```

## Mandatory Rules

### Step-Pair Pattern

Every register read uses a step pair -- odd step triggers, even step waits and parses. Never read results in the same step that set `bExecute`. Separating trigger and result into distinct cycles guarantees the FB has at least one cycle to process the request.

### Busy Guard

Always wrap trigger steps in `IF NOT bReadBusy THEN`. Prevents enqueueing while previous request is in flight. Essential for RTU FIFO; defensive best practice for TCP.

### Reserved Step Numbers

| Range | Purpose |
|-------|---------|
| 0 | Idle -- wait for interval timer |
| 1-29 | Global read steps (device-wide data) |
| 30 | Loop entry (multi-device: calculate base address) |
| 50 | Loop control (advance to next sub-device or complete) |
| 90 | Success handler |
| 100 | Error handler |
| 200 | Shared delay step |

Write state machine: same convention with `_nWriteStep`. Write data steps typically start at 10.

### Execute Flag Pattern

Set `_bReadExecute` inside CASE step. Call communication FB once after all CASE blocks. Clear flag unconditionally after call. Guarantees exactly one rising edge per request.

### Interval Timer

Self-resetting TON with minimum T#100MS enforcement. Prevents retriggering during active read cycle.

### Error Counter Pattern

Two counters: consecutive (resets on success) and total (never resets). Capture error address and error ID on failure. `_nReadNextStep` is set in the even (wait) step before jumping to 90/100, NOT in step 90 itself.

### Dual State Machine

Read and write run as independent CASE state machines in the same FB cycle. Each has own step variable, delay timer, next-step variable, and error handling. Write must not block reads.

### Register Constants Inside FB

Device-specific register addresses, timing, and limits are `VAR CONSTANT` inside the FB. Never in a GVL. Keeps device knowledge self-contained.

### Data Struct Design

One `ST_[Device]_Data` struct per device. Document each field with unit `[V]`, gain, and register offset in a comment.

### Register Gap Handling

Never read across reserved/non-existent register addresses. Split into separate step pairs.

### 32-Bit Word Order (Big-Endian)

First register (lower address) = HIGH word. Always verify against device datasheet. Swapping HIGH/LOW produces values off by factor 65536.

### Sentinel Values

Helper functions check for "not-implemented" sentinels (0xFFFF, 0x8000, 0xFFFFFFFF, 0x80000000) and substitute 0 with `bValid := FALSE`.

### IEEE 754 FLOAT32

Use `POINTER TO REAL` for bit-reinterpretation. Never `DWORD_TO_REAL` (value conversion, not bit cast -- always wrong for IEEE 754).

### Signed Write Values

Convert via `REAL_TO_INT` then `INT_TO_WORD`. Never `REAL_TO_WORD` (clips negatives to 0).

### Write Change Detection

Store last-written values in a memory struct. Only trigger write when input changed or explicit trigger set.

### Data Buffer Sizing

TCP: `ARRAY[0..N] OF WORD` (0-based). Size must be >= the largest single query (nQuantity). Max 125 registers per read.
RTU: `ARRAY[1..N] OF BYTE` (1-based). Size must be >= `nQuantity * 2` bytes. Max ~20 registers per read.

## Coding Principles

1. One FB per device type -- all device knowledge encapsulated inside the FB
2. Identical state machine skeleton -- control flow (0 -> steps -> 90/100 -> 200 -> next) never changes
3. No blocking constructs -- never use WHILE, REPEAT, or spin-loops
4. One FB call per cycle -- communication FBs called once, after all CASE blocks
5. Minimal variable scope -- buffers and steps private (`_`), only `stData` and diagnostics exposed
6. Transport layer is the only variable -- when porting TCP to RTU, only VAR_INPUT, FB type, buffer type, and conversion functions change
